#week-title("One", "The Via Humida: Philosophy & First Principle")

=== Core Teaching

The Wet Path (*Via Humida*) approaches the mineral kingdom through the medium
of water and solvents — gradually extracting, dissolving, and reconstituting
mineral substances without the violence of high fire. This is the natural entry
point for the Adept whose first two years have been spent mastering the
vegetable and water kingdoms: the Via Humida extends the same fundamental
operations — dissolution, separation, cohobation — into mineral territory.

Bartlett writes of the Via Humida: "There are some experiments we can do which
lie at a borderline between the Vegetable and Mineral worlds." The first mineral
preparations of Year Three exist precisely at this border. The student who has
done the Year Two Month 7 border cohobation work and the Month 10 wine vinegar
experiments has already been working in the Pre-Via Humida territory.

*The principle of gradual approach.* The Wet Path proceeds without sudden
violence. Where the Via Sicca (Dry Path) employs high fusion temperatures that
instantaneously transform mineral substances, the Via Humida works through
successive dissolution cycles at moderate temperatures. The mineral substance
is:

1. *Dissolved* in the appropriate acid medium — this is the analogue of
   maceration in the vegetable work.
2. The resulting solution is *evaporated* — the analogue of distillation;
   the volatile carries off and the salt concentrates.
3. The salt is *recovered* — calcined or simply dried — and then
4. *Cohobated* again with a fresh portion of the dissolving medium, each
   cycle drawing the mineral's virtue more completely out of its matrix.

Each cycle in the Via Humida corresponds to one separation and reunion of the
three principles at the mineral level — the same movement as the Year One
spagyric work, but operating at the mineral degree of fixity and requiring
correspondingly more cycles to achieve genuine elevation.

*Choice of first mineral.* The student selects one of the following for the
Month 2 Via Humida work:
- *Antimony (stibnite):* Continuing directly from Month 1; the acid medium
  is dilute acetic acid (strong wine vinegar) or dilute hydrochloric acid
  (advanced option, requiring acid-resistant PPE).
- *Iron (iron nail or filing):* Accessible, non-toxic, responsive to vinegar
  and dilute mineral acids; the Mars mineral.
- *Copper (copper sheet or shavings):* Produces striking colour changes with
  vinegar; the Venus mineral.

=== Topics This Week

- The Via Humida as the extension of vegetable spagyric operations into mineral
- The four-stage cycle: dissolution, evaporation, recovery, cohobation
- Philosophical equivalences: mineral dissolution = maceration; evaporation =
  distillation; recovered salt = calcined ash
- Choosing the first mineral substrate for Month 2 work

#inner-work[
  *The Slow Path*

  The Via Humida demands extraordinary patience: cycles that took weeks in the
  vegetable kingdom now take months in the mineral kingdom. Sit with this
  requirement for twenty minutes.

  What does it reveal about your relationship to time and result at this stage
  of the Work? How has two years of practice changed your baseline capacity for
  patience compared to where you began in Year One Month 1? Record honestly.
]

